children.text:
Alright, so this is [INTERVIEWER'S NAME] from [COMMUNITY NAME]. Today is June 17th, and I'm
here in [COMMUNITY NAME] for an interview with one of our community members. And before we
begin, I'd like to get a verbal consent for the form that we went over. Could you please say "I consent to
being interviewed and audio recorded for this study?"
I consent to be interviewed and audio recorded for this study.

Excellent. And we're just going to jump right in. So to get started, can you tell me about how you came
to live in this community?

I was born and raised in this community. I went to school from first through 12th grade. Do you need
anything other than that?
No.
I still live in this community.
That sounds great.
Yeah.
And could you tell me a little bit more about the community?
Back then? Now is good- Or now?
Whatever perspective you have on it.

It was a small town when I first, when I was born and when I went to school. The kind that you ride
your bicycle to school, because it's not very far away. I enjoyed it being a small town, you knew
everybody in our went to church with everybody in this town in one way or another. You'd either grown
up with them, knew brothers andor sisters, that sort of thing. I wouldn't trade that experience for
anything about growing up in a small town.
That all sounds great. I'm sure you miss it.
It is.
It sounds so pleasant.

It is nice having a grocery store. Back then we did have a grocery store, but not for everything, you
know. But for most of everything, you you could get it here. You had a train that ran through the center
of downtown all the time, and which I lived in the center of downtown, and you wake up to the trains in
the morning and don't even know if you, they even run here anymore. But my dad was the town
plumber, and my mother worked for the school in the cafeteria. So everything was [COMMUNITY
NAME] here

That sounds so interesting to me, and you explained it so well. Is there a specific way that you would
describe [COMMUNITY NAME] to someone who doesn't live here?

Back then, it was a secret to Downtown. I, I did not re-, I, I really didn't discuss [COMMUNITY NAME]
before I, I worked [DIFFERENT NORTH TEXAS REGION COMMUNITY NAME], uh, for an attorney for,
uh, insurance for years. Six years anyway, and then I had my daughter, uh, but I, I wouldn't. A-and
repeat the question again.
Yeah, of course
Exactly what you said.
Is there a way that you would describe [COMMUNITY NAME] to someone who doesn't live here?

And the reason I say secret is because you're young, I own my first car. It was a cute little red sports
car. I took it to the very top of [STREET NAME] here. At the time, we did not have the light that is there
now, it was farmland and things that direction. But the massive hill went down, and all you could see
were the mountains around here. And I, I'm, I'm used to that, I grew up here. Uh, I didn't think anything
about it. I took my picture to work, put it on my desk, and everybody that came by said "you've been to
Colorado"? And I said, no, that's [COMMUNITY NAME]. No, there's nothing like that in [COMMUNITY
NAME]. And I said "yes there is, you should get out more often." And driving through like the [STREET
NAME], which is still that way, with tree canopies close over the road as you're driving through them.
That's my calming drive. I do that occasionally just a calm, you know, a nice, cool, calm drive. And I still
do that.
To this day? wow.
Yes, to this day.

I can imagine how relaxing that, that would feel. And you've already touched on this a little bit, but how
do you think [COMMUNITY NAME] has changed throughout your time living here?

Um, in about 1987, people discovered us. Uh, people wanted this and wanted their families, um, to
grow up here too. And we began to grow. Um, but at that time, there was one elementary school and
one high school and one junior high. But there weren't very many kids, there were about, when I was in
first grade, I would say there were 200 kids in all of school-
Wow.

-here. There weren't a lot of kids. And of course now in 93, I think my daughter, I don't know, I don't
even remember how many but 1000 or so maybe, you know, and she's almost 50 years old. So it's, it's
grown immensely since then, and everything has grown. Your, your wheat and corn fields have
disappeared and houses and businesses and things have popped up. The only town we had was here,
the original old downtown, which is just a town square, the main highway used to come through there,
there were no highways anywhere, um, and it went down [STREET NAME] used to be the highway
here. So it's, it's a very different, then they opened [HIGHWAY NAME]. And there were a little bit on it,
but not much, mainly a gas station, little place to eat, little insurance company, family, all of them family
kind of places. And, uh, but that part of it seems to have grown immensely, you know, the population
grew. But from 1987, um, is about the time that it started. And I don't think any of us, you had in, uh, for
instance, in the City Hall that we had was downtown. It had the Fire Department with what vehicles we
have in it. It had the Tax Office, it had the Water Department, it had Finance, it had Public Works. It
had, not a Police Department, but a County Office there. Uh, it had the City Manager's little office, the
council room was in it. Every, we really didn't have Code back then, you know, they were getting that
and they had to because of all the building that was beginning. You had to come up with code. I
actually have my parents had a summer house in the lake, and they still didn't have codes there. So
you ended up having this beautiful palatial house and right beside it, there was a tire company, you
know, um, we had the foresight, I assume back then, to think of those things first, and otherwise, it
might have been very different than it is now. But that was town, there was nothing else. There was
nothing else. The high school going in on [HIGHWAY NAME], in 1961. I'm part of a reunion group here.
And it went it was built in 61. And there was like a few things then that went a little further down
[HIGHWAY NAME], like a Freez-ett, which is a Dairy Queen, nowadays, those kinds of things, but
mainly still just homes. And that's the only homes there were, was just in that small area that was
around town.
That's very, it's so hard for me to picture, you know?
t's very different. It's so different. So different now.
mmensely different. And it's still growing, you see construction everywhere.
Oh, yes. And there's no more cornfields-
[LAUGHS]

-there's no more wheat, there's no more, uh, there's just houses and a lake now that went in in 84,
1984. Then the lake went in. So, and that's been a draw for a lot of people. "Oh, they have a lake, I
think I'll move there." You know? So there's a lot of draw out here to this part. It still looks country. But
it's not exactly country anymore.
You explained it so well. Wow. It's, it's just changed so much.

It's, it's changed 100% since when I grew up. The one thing I'll say that, you could ride your bicycle
through town when I was very young, but you could ride your bicycle, you needed a drink of water, you
could stop at Aunt so and so's house, not my aunt, but somebody's, and they give you drink water.
Also, if you did anything wrong, by the time you got home, your parents had already heard about it
because all these people had called and said "Oh, so and so I was throwing rocks" and blah, blah, blah,
you know, something like that. Not me, but, I was a good kid. I was a good student. But, uh, you know,
everybody knows everybody.
And what would you say are some strengths of [COMMUNITY NAME]?

I really, I really think that the city itself has hired and thought about the right people. We would have
never thought about having an Economic Development Department until all the businesses became
interested, as [COMMUNITY NAME] blossomed, and Economic Development is, at one time or
another, I was a Secretary for every department in the Government Center because they were all in the
Government Center. So when ED, they started in there in the Government Center had everybody had a
closet or something for an office. And so you were familiar with what they were there the reason for
being here, the concerns that they had about choosing the proper businesses for us. And I think along
the reason [COMMUNITY NAME] has grown as much if not more than the cities around here is they put
everything in line as they needed it. And they had the knowledge and the information. And if they didn't
have it, they, they looked for it, uh, out to other cities that were about our size that were having this kind
of growth spurt, you know, it wasn't just as deciding, if they took their information to and said "Hmm,
okay, maybe we need to think about different things." And Fire, Fire and Police are definitely going to
have to be beefed up when you start having more people. And so, that's another thing that always got
handled, was Fire and Police has to be be-beefed up. So they were always a concern. Of course you, I
used to answer the phone all the time and somebody will say "Can you send the Street Department out
to so and so and so and so?" And I said, "Ma'am, we have two people in the Street Department. Uh, I, I
doubt if those two people are going to be able, maybe I can get in touch with some of them to get in
touch with you and see what the issues are that you're having, and they can advise you." But you know,
it's not that we have a lot of people that work for us. Uh, but the city is always here to answer your
questions, but, uh, we don't have the people. People wanted to know where our snow shovels were,
you know, when it snows, which it snows here, it usually doesn't snow even in a year. It might, but it
doesn't. So no, we don't have snow shovels. We use bulldozers because that's all we got is that. We
can use them for other things. Otherwise, that snow mach-machine would be sitting on the corner over
there. Bu, uh, yes, we have, they had the peace of mind and the, the knowledge to see, these are
machines that, these are what we need to purchase, because they can not only be, have to be used by
street, our Parks Department could use those, you know. Occasionally some of the other departments
might need something that we could use that machine for. So it was a share. Everything got shared,
and I guess it still does, I don't know.

Yeah. And I was, I was able to learn a little bit about the ED Department the other day here. They have
a very important job.

We had a, we had an, uh, an gentleman that had been a director, an ED director, other places when he
came. His name was [DIRECTOR'S NAME], and he was perfect for us because he, he was concerned
with, we have a lot of old businesses that have been here a long time. And he was still interested in the
old businesses, as well as what's new, and what do we need. You know, we may not need this type of
business here, but then we might need this business here. And that, that takes a lot of forethought to
figure that out.

Yes, and that's also a very good perspective to have because then people in the city can kind of get the
best of both worlds.
Yes.

Yeah, and what would you say are some weaknesses of the community if there are any, in your
opinion?

I really don't, I really don't know of a weakness because if there ever has been, it's always been
addressed. Even if it's a temporary weakness. It's always been addressed. Uh, many years ago, we
used to dispatch some of the departments from the front of the City Hall. We dispatched Animal Control
and, and things that couldn't be housed up there. They had a different place, but I, I don't really think
that there was ever a weakness. Uh, occasionally I will say, for any instance, you may have to call
Parks or something to help, we had one Animal Control Officer to begin with, all of that grows, and
when you start having more people, you've got more need there. Occasionally we had to pull in Parks
or somebody from Parks to come help us to do that for the day or something, not saying they wanted
to, but they, you know, you had to have somebody to assist. Uh, and, and it was all, that it was all taken
well, back then. Nobody, nobody griped about it, because you knew it, they wouldn't have called you, if
it hadn't been a nec-necessity.

I'm glad that all problems were able to be figured out. I feel like a lot of cities can't say that they, that
they do that, you know? So it's really great that it was hard for you to think of a weakness, I think that's
a very-

Weakness, but you know, there's things that have to wait. I mean, there was, there's always, yes,
there's roads that run down quicker than they should, or quicker than you ever expected them to. And
we just, you have to live with a promise, you know, "We're, we're getting to that it's on our list to do, and
it's, it's on our priority, and we've got a priority list, and that's what, we're going to we're going to work
on that.
And can you tell me about the roles and relationships that you have in this community?

I'm part of a reunion group, from people that graduated from 1931 to 1981. Yes, people in 1931 for the
most part are gone. Uh, I have a lot of things in my family now that take up my time, that take me away
from that, but I've been a part of it for a long time. And they still ask me occasionally certain things if I
can do and I will. But, uh, I was a part of, uh, a member of a church. I sang in choir I, uh, I worked. I
worked and volunteered anything to do here. Uh, I always lived close to the city hall, so if it's a snow
day or an ice day, if I couldn't get here, somebody came and got me because I just live six minutes
away, you know. I don't live in another city. There are, to begin with most of us did live in this city. And
of course, now that's, that's probably not the, I don't know, but I would imagine that's not the case
anymore. Firemen and Police, uh, don't particularly live in what city they work for. But...

And while we're on the topic of your roles in the community, I know that you are, uh, I know that you've
left working, but can you tell me a little bit more about what you did when you were working here?

I was an Executive Assistant for the Assistant City Manager, was my major role for 25 years. Uh, that
could have been anything. It could have been, I knew about the city because I was born and raised
here. So I think I was an advocate for the city. And what happened before, my boss used to say, come
to me occasionally, because he's wasn't from here. Uh, he was from [DIFFERENT NORTH TEXAS
REGION COMMUNITY NAME], and he would say "So in the olden days", and I would say, "Are you
calling me old?", and he goes, "No, in the days before I got here, you know, how did so and so, how did
this happen? Or how did you, how did y'all handle this?" I felt like sometimes when we were small city
hall, I answered a lot of the, the day to day needs that people had. I was, my extension was 1010, I was
that person that had been here all their life, and if you want to know, if you'll call me, I'll, I'll find out the
answer for you. I like people. I, I don't know what I would, if you put me in a room the rest of my life, I
do not think I would be happy. I like to visit with people, I like to talk to people I like to see where they're
from, what their concerns are. Sometimes you don't want to hear some of their concerns because
there's no way you can make things see or heal like some huge, huge city with a bunch more people
than we are. We have to dealing with what our population is and what we can do for our population.
We're not 150,000 people. we're more like 50,000. So, uh, you have to constantly remember, you may
have came from a larger city here. You may not have everything available to you that you had in a
larger city. But it could be coming, and that's a good idea, so you want to keep those things. I used to
have a thing written down about strange calls and things you might need and stuff like that, and I kept it
for years and I gave it to somebody when I retired up here, I don't know if they continue that. But I
always thought it was, uh, for instance. I think it was a second day I was here and I worked in Utility
Billing. The phone rang, and of course, anything there to do with the phone was always me anyway,
and I answered the phone, and this lady said, "Are the Mustang grapes ripe yet?" I didn't say anything
for a second, I said "Ma'am, you've reached the Water Department for the City of [COMMUNITY
NAME]." "Yes, I know. Are the Mustang grapes ripe yet?" So I had an older lady, I told you everybody
worked in that same area. "Hold on, please." I put her on hold. The lady, she's, I had, I went to school
with her daughter. She worked in accoun-, she was the accounting person. And I said "Wilma, I have
this lady just asking me are the ripe, what, Mustang grapes ready yet? And she goes "Yeah, tell them
they are, I went by there this morning. They are so." "Yes, ma'am, Mustang grapes are are ready now."
And obviously, I didn't know that. They grew on vines. Where the big towers, we have all these huge
towers here. Uh, on the outside of the fences, where the towers are, and they allowed people to come
get them and make jelly out of them. I didn't know that. So then I learned a new thing. You learn
something new every day too when you work somewhere like this, where you talk to different people. I
like that though.

I, I, I love that too, I love learning new things. And that specific situation, would have, I would have told
that story over and over again.

Well, it was my first, and that's one of the reasons I started writing it down in the book. So, you know,
some things, I might forget that, probably never, but I might forget that. But I wrote it down, and I wrote
other things that people, you know, had said. Uh, people would call and say, you know, "There's a
donkey on [HIGHWAY NAME] going south." "Well, thank you very much. I'll find Animal Control." You
know, there's a donkey on the [HIGHWAY NAME]! And, but it was a small town. And it was fun to, to
work in a small town with just a few people.
I'm glad you passed on that notebook. I hope whoever you gave it to still has it.

I hope too. I think, uh, [EMPLOYEE'S NAME] here with them. I don't know, I, I had so many people ask
me strangest things. Uh, worked for the Water Department, person calls me one day and says "Which,
which costs more, hot or cold water?" and I said "Well, eventually hot water is going to cost you more
because you have to have it. You have to, you have a hot water heater in your house and you heat the
water, but all the water comes in at the same temperature. So, cold water is all you get and then you,
your, your house deals with how to heat it," Now, it went on my list, because I thought that's strange
question to ask. But a lot of people live in apartments. They don't have a clue, you know, they have no
idea how exactly their house really worked. And, uh, I don't know it took me aback. That one, that one
hit me further than the Mustang grapes then, because my dad was a plumber [LAUGHS]. But, you
know, some things were funny, they entertain you when people had questions. And sometimes it was
sad. Uh, but I wanted to help. I worked here because I liked to help people. If I could help you in any
way, shape or form, give me the question and if I don't know it, I'll find it out and I'll call you. And that's,
that's was my logo tag, whatever it was, that I could do that and I enjoyed doing that. And I still enjoy
doing that. Except people still call me and I've been gone 12 years, so I don't know now. Even who is
over a particular department, you know, things like that, but it's still humorous, as I always say, "You
know, I've been gone 12 years." "Yes, but can you find out?" "Sure, I can find out, and I'll call you
back."

And that's such a good mentality to have, I think it can get you so far in life and give you so many
connections. And speaking of connections, how do you think some of your connections in this
community influenced your work as an Executive Assistant?

I just think some of the employees, I'm pretty sure they handed out my, my phone number, you know,
from, from the Water Department to whoever else it was in here, uh, "I don't know, but you might want
to try 1010." You know? And that was okay with me. That was okay with me. Because if you've got to
have a place and, you know, I'm, I'm wasn't, I wouldn't say that I was the last, the last person you talk
to, you know, it may be that I need to give that to the Assistant City Manager, or maybe that's a Mayor
thing, that the, the Mayor had an office in ours, and it wasn't a, it's not a paid position, it isn't to this day,
but he was here a lot, and he answered a lot of questions, and he did a lot of proclamations, and, uh,
for certain days and certain people. And they honored people. Uh, I don't know, I really, I enjoyed that. I
don't, I had been asked why I I stayed in Administration and didn't go somewhere else, and it's just
because it's something that suited me. It suited me from the time I first started working, because I
worked for attorneys then. And it, it seemed like it suited me always, so, I felt like I was in the right
place. I never felt out of place. So you might as well work for something where you fill in, and you don't
feel out of place.

I'm very glad to hear that. I think that's crucial, uh, when it comes to working, because you don't want to
be stuck somewhere you don't want to be.

I don't think you'll do a good job if you get stuck somewhere you don't want to be. Uh, it's hard to give
your all when you don't enjoy it yourself.

Absolutely, I'm with you on that. It's been so interesting hearing about your job, and I'd like to ask more
questions about it. Some of the stuff we've already discussed.
Okay.

You have already given me the answers, but it'd be great to hear about them again. The first thing I
want to ask you is if you could tell me about how you got into the role of an Executive Assistant

You know, I can't tell you that because I don't know. I, I answered the job. I needed a full time job. I
worked Downtown. I didn't want to drive back and forth. I had a child that was here in this school. I
wanted to be able to do things whenever she had programs and things, and this city was always family
first, and I thought "That's where I want to be." The position came up for a part-time person in the
library. I love reading and library was my favorite. I really wanted to end my job there, but it just didn't
happen. But, uh, the library was my favorite, I, just one lady was over the library. And another lady had
been before and that was [EMPLOYEE'S NAME] that this library here is, uh, she and I went to church
together. And I knew her and her daughters were same, uh, one of them was about same age I was so,
library sounds like a good thing. Small library, one room in the hallway to the Government Center.
That's what the library was. One room in the library to the Government Center. Anyway, uh, uh, and I
forgot what you were asking me.
Yeah, I was just saying how, how did you get into the role?

Okay, it, and the job came up then. Not in part-time in the Water Department. So, they were in the
same building, so I worked part-time in the library and switched to part-time in the Water Department.
And then the next thing I knew, I still worked in the Water Department but we had an Assistant City
Manager, he needed an Assistant. "[INTERVIEWEE'S NAME], can you be his Assistant?" "Sure I can:"
"You stay here in Water and still help with the Water window, but you will be his Assistant." And then
they changed the building around and things, and I went then straight to the Assist-, we grew. And, uh,
they moved, uh, Public Works to a different location, Animal Control was moved to a different location.
And, uh, we still had, a lot of the departments that we were still working for, actually I'm the one that
also, if somebody needed desk, or, uh, there, "We got a new person coming, where are we going to put
them? What are we going to, we need a desk." And I would go see how big a place we had for them,
what would fit in that place. And then I had a place that I could go and usually find the furniture and be
here. That was another thing. I, I was happy with any role that they gave me. Whatever they needed,
they knew they could depend on me to find it. But the, the short is they, they were asking for part time
people. And I thought, "This is me and my chance to get my foot in the door. And maybe I will be there
if there's a full time position that stays, then I will be able to stay and work in this city where my child is."
Now, my parents lived across the street, and where I grew up, so it wasn't far for me to even visit with
my child if I wanted to. But, uh, she benefited and I benefited.
I'm glad to hear that it sounds like you did so much in your time here. And how long did you work here?

30 years, give or take a couple of months I think. I came in '82 and I retired in 2012. Uh, I will hold
something I was going to tell you for later, because I think you'll ask me that too.
Okay. We will, we will see.
Yeah.
And you've already mentioned that you did so much and that everyday looked different for you?
uh-huh
But if you could, how would you describe a typical workday?

It was nonstop. As I said, we, the, the, the switchboard didn't switch over to actually, we, we could put
thing-, I mean things went to an answering system until eight o'clock, and then your phone started
ringing. And your boss's phone usually was on yours as well as on his or their, or hers. And so it was, it
was nonstop for me from morning to night and night then sometimes went into other things. Uh, if you
were si-, uh, Assistant City Manager, well, he's going to council meetings, so there were things that you
had to, uh, stay sometimes and help with them. I, e-, we all paid department bills back then. And I paid,
uh, I paid bills, and I liked staying after hours because otherwise we were in a cubicle when we moved
into this building, and there was always somebody there. The only real quiet time you had to be able to
make sure everything is paid, I have this thing, I'm, uh, I'm a detail person. I like detail. My daughter has
just decided over this last few weeks. Of course, I said she's 50, but she's decided that we are getting
more and more and more alike, because I will jump in there with details, she will jump in there will
detail, and all of a sudden you're at your wit's end, you know, so, uh, I like detail. I like certain things in
order. Uh, uh, and I've always liked it that way and order. And go back to what you were asking me
again, I forgot
Yeah, I think you answered it pretty well. I was just asking about what a typical workday looked like

It was, it was hectic. You never knew. You never knew and if there was anything that came up during
the day, and it required you to be here a little while longer, you were here longer. The fun thing was this
building used to backup to property that nobody had ever lived on before. Oh, that's not true, but then I
knew, before me I'm sure it probably did. Uh, but I would always like to have the last lunch hour
because I wanted everybody to have whatever they wanted to do, go ahead and plan it. I knew that at
one, I could have the last lunch hour. And so I didn't come in until two, one to two. So that made my
afternoon better a lot of times. But at night, if you were still here at council, or something, and it got late,
I got the last parking place in the back of the back of the back of the parking lot, and one day, one night,
the next morning, I come in and I asked my boss, I said, "There were these little eyes, looking at me
from the bushes, and I was terrified." And he goes, "Oh, they're foxes. They're the little foxes. And I
think there's some new ones that were back there, I see that too." And I thought, "Well, you know, I'll
take your word for it, but I'm not really sure I'm happy with the wildlife, you know, that close, and I'm
sitting there, the only car in the parking lot sometimes in two or three parts. That's it. And so it was kind
of scary [LAUGHS]. But the days were long, and if they were short, that was a blessing. If you had to be
gone, there was always somebody that could do it, you know, that would volunteer say "I'll do it. Don't
worry, you go-", you know. My parents were older when I was born, so therefore, by the time I had my
daughter, and they, they were a lot more elderly, and I had to speak to them. So there's some things
that came up after my work hours sometimes that I had to do, and I was allowed to do that. If it was an
emergency, there was no problem.
It just, it sounds like a very healthy workplace. And I can see why you-

My husband said one day when I said something, like I just said to you, he got quiet. And I said,
"What's the matter?" and he said, "I don't think I've ever worked for a place like that, that I was that
happy with who I worked with and what I did." So I count myself lucky. I count that. I think I'm, I'm a
religious person, I think things guide me. My pathway a little bit, give me a little inkling to go this way or
that way, you know, and, uh, that I don't know, I've just, I just, he took me back, I couldn't, I didn't have
anything to say, but I did feel lucky that I did have something like that. Working downtown was, was,
was not my place to be, I was not comfortable there but, uh, I tolerated it very well I think.
I think you got lucky too, and I'm very glad that you were able to be in a place like that.
Yeah.

I'm very happy for you. And what would you say it means to to have been an Executive Assistant in this
community?

I, I felt that somebody thought I was worthy of it. That it was, as I believed something I was meant to be,
meant to do, put on this Earth to do. And, uh, I did not have that opportunity when I worked downtown
to do that kind of thing, really. So it was, uh, uh, I, I didn't feel like I was, had, I, I had a responsibility,
but I don't think I had any more responsibility than anybody else probably had. But, uh, I thought what I
